        "observed_type": "title",
        "canon_role": "section_header",
        "text": "Phosphorus and nitrogen absorption",
        "bbox": [
          0.5276601313812778,
          0.21950093040539445,
          0.818377337524466,
          0.23618813564089228
        ],
        "order": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "mineru_docstructbench_llm-raw-scihub-o.O-j.1444-2906.2002.00466.x.pdf_4_6",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Table 4 shows the absorption rates of P and N in carp fed the different diets. The P absorption rate (% of dietary P) was inversely proportional to the total dietary P content. The highest P absorption rate as a percentage of total P was observed for the diet lowest in FM (diet 5), followed by diet groups 3 and 4. The available P calculated from the absorption rates was approximately similar to the estimated dietary available P (water-extractable P), and all diets met the level required by carp (0.6–0.7%). The determined available P was slightly lower (0.76%) than that of the estimated value (0.82%) for the control group. Nitrogen absorption was signifi cantly higher (P<0.05) in the control group and lowest for diet 2. There were no signifi- cant differences (P>0.05) in these values among the experimental groups.",
        "bbox": [
          0.5259796851029935,
          0.25030807853246734,
          0.9108018828301038,
          0.5018997882368961
        ],
        "order": 6
      }
    ]
  },
